{"question": {"text": "\r\n\r\nIn many scripts I inherited from a former employee I keep seeing this pattern:\n\nif (true $SOME_VAR)&>/dev/null; then\n    ...\nfi\n\n\nor this one \n\n(true $SOME_VAR)&>/dev/null || SOME_VAR=\"...\"\n\n\nThe man page for true says it always returns true, hence I keep wondering, what is the point of these checks? In the first case the then part is always executed, in the second case the right hand part is never executed. \n    ", "date_asked": "2017-03-27 12:13:58Z"}, "author": {"name": "Eli Korvigo", "link": "/users/3846213/eli-korvigo"}}
{"question": {"text": "\r\n\r\nI am trying to install elasticsearch on Windows. I am following the corresponding guide.\n\nIn step two (Running Elasticsearch from the command line), I get the following error:\n\n\n  You must set the ES_CLASSPATH var\n\n\n\n\nHere is what I did:\n\n\nI downloaded the .zip package\nI unzipped the package to \"c:\\elasticsearch-5.3.0\"\n$ cd \"c:\\elasticsearch-5.3.0\"\n\n\nThen I ran:\n\n$ \".\\bin\\elasticsearch\"\nYou must set the ES_CLASSPATH var\n\n\n\n\nNote: I know from this answer, that the elasticsearch.in.sh file needs to be in the right directory, but I never changed the location of it and I have all permissions\n    ", "date_asked": "2017-04-02 10:00:22Z"}, "author": {"name": "jonhue", "link": "/users/6561814/jonhue"}}
